'''Jesse LeRoy Brown''' (13 October 1926{{spaced ndash}}4 December 1950) was a [[United States Navy]] officer. He was the first African-American [[naval aviator|aviator]] in the U.S. Navy, a recipient of the Distinguished Flying Cross, and the first African-American naval officer killed in the [[Korean War]].

Born in [[Hattiesburg, Mississippi]], to an impoverished family, Brown was avidly interested in aircraft from a young age. He graduated as [[salutatorian]] of his high school, notwithstanding its [[Racial segregation in the United States|racial segregation]], and was later awarded a degree from [[Ohio State University]]. Brown enlisted in the U.S. Navy in 1946, becoming a [[midshipman]]. Brown earned his [[United States Aviator Badge|pilot wings]] on 21 October 1948 amid a flurry of press coverage; in January 1949 he was assigned to [[VF-32|Fighter Squadron 32]] aboard the {{USS|Leyte|CV-32|6}}.

At the outset of the Korean War, the ''Leyte'' was ordered to the [[Korean Peninsula]], arriving in October 1950. Brown, an [[Ensign (rank)#United States|ensign]], flew 20 combat missions before his [[F4U Corsair]] aircraft came under fire and crashed on a remote mountaintop on 4 December 1950 while supporting ground troops at the [[Battle of Chosin Reservoir]]. Brown died of his wounds despite the efforts of wingman [[Thomas J. Hudner, Jr.]], who intentionally crashed his own aircraft in a rescue attempt, for which he was awarded the [[Medal of Honor]].

Brown's successes in the [[Racial discrimination against African-Americans in the U.S. Military|segregated and desegregated]] U.S. military were memorialized in several books.  The frigate {{USS|Jesse L. Brown|FF-1089}} was named in his honor.

== Early life and education ==
Brown was born on 13 October 1926 in Hattiesburg, Mississippi.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=38}}{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=60}} He was one of six children born to Julia Lindsey Brown, a schoolteacher, and John Brown, a grocery warehouse worker.{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}} He had four brothers, Marvin, William, Fletcher, and Johnny, as well as a sister, Lura. Brown's ancestry was African American, [[Chicksaw]], and [[Choctaw]].{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=23}} The family lived in a house without [[central heating]] or [[indoor plumbing]] so they relied on a [[fireplace]] for warmth. As a child, Jesse's brother William fell into this fireplace and was severely burned.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=39}}

At the beginning of the [[Great Depression]], John Brown lost his job and relocated the family to Palmer's Crossing, {{convert|10|mi}} from Hattiesburg, where he worked at a [[turpentine]] factory until he was laid off in 1938.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=26}} John Brown then moved the family to Lux, Mississippi, to be a part of a [[sharecropper]] farm.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=39}} During this time, Jesse Brown shared a bed with his brothers and attended a one-room school {{convert|3|mi}} away. His parents were very strict about school attendance and homework, and Jesse Brown walked to school every day.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=28}} The Browns also were committed [[Baptists]] and Jesse, William, and Julia Brown sang in the [[church choir]].{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=39}} In his spare time, Brown also worked in the fields of the farm harvesting corn and cotton.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=27}}

When Brown was six years old, his father took him to an [[air show]].{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=25}} Brown gained an intense interest in flying from this experience, and afterward, was attracted to a dirt airfield near his home, which he visited frequently in spite of being chased away by a local mechanic.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=39}}

At the age of thirteen, Brown took a job as a [[paperboy (newspaper delivery)|paperboy]] for the ''[[Pittsburgh Courier]]'', a [[black press]] paper,{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=30}} and developed a desire to pilot while reading in the newspaper about African-American aviators of the time including [[C. Alfred Anderson]], [[Eugine Jacques Bullard]], and [[Bessie Coleman]].{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=39}} He also became an avid reader of ''[[Popular Aviation]]'' and the ''[[Chicago Defender]]'', which he later said heavily influenced his desire to fly naval aircraft.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=9}} In his childhood he was described as "serious, witty, unassuming, and very intelligent."{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}} In 1937, he wrote a letter to U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] in which he complained of the injustice of African-American pilots being kept out of the [[U.S. Army Air Corps]], to which the [[White House]] responded with a letter saying that it appreciated the viewpoint.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=31}}

[[File:Jesse L. Brown 1948.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Brown as a midshipman in Jacksonville, Florida in 1947|alt=A young man in a naval uniform.]]

Because the schools closer to his family were of lower quality, in 1939, Brown lived with his aunt and attended the [[segregation in the United States|segregated]] [[Eureka School (Hattiesburg, Mississippi)|Eureka High School]] in Hattiesburg.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=39}} He was a member of the basketball, [[American football|football]], and track and field teams {{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}} and he was an excellent student, graduating as the salutatorian in 1944.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=60}}{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=39}} During this time, Brown met his future wife, Daisy Pearl Nix.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=39}}

Following graduation, Brown sought to enroll in a college outside of the [[Southern United States|South]]. His principal, Nathaniel Burger, advised he attend an all-black college, as his brother Marvin Brown had done, however, he ended up enrolling at [[Ohio State University]] as his childhood role model, [[Jesse Owens]], had done. Burger told Brown only seven African Americans had graduated from the school that year, but Brown nonetheless was determined to enroll, feeling he would compete well with white students.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=40}}

Brown took several side jobs to save money for college, including waiting tables at the Holmes Club, a saloon for white [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] soldiers. In this job, Brown was frequently the target of racist vitriol and abuse, but nonetheless persevered, earning $600 to pay for college.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=40}} In the autumn of 1944, Brown took a segregated train to [[Columbus, Ohio]], and began school at Ohio State.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=8}}

Brown moved into an on-campus [[boarding house]] at 61 East Eleventh Avenue in the primarily black neighborhood of the University District in Columbus,{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=10}} and majored in [[architectural engineering]]. Brown attempted several times to apply to the school's aviation program, but was denied because of his race.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=12}} Brown joined the track and field team as well as the [[wrestling]] team, but soon dropped both for financial reasons. He took a job as a janitor at a local [[Lazarus (department store)|Lazarus]] [[department store]] and then was hired by the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] to load [[boxcar]]s from 15:30 to midnight each day.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=40}} In spite of this, he maintained top grades in his classes.{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}} Facing difficulties with his academics and the institutional segregation in the city, Brown nevertheless found most of his fellow students were friendly toward him.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=11}} Brown rarely returned to Mississippi during the school year, but in the summers he worked at a [[dry cleaner]] in Hattiesburg to help pay for his classes.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=15}}

During his second year in college, Brown learned of the V-5 [[Aviation Cadet Training Program (USN)|Aviation Cadet Training Program]] being conducted by the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] to commission [[naval aviation]] pilots.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=60}} This program operated at 52 colleges, none of which were predominantly black colleges, so only students such as Brown, who attended integrated colleges, were eligible.{{sfn|MacGregor|1981|pp=246â€“247}} In spite of resistance from recruiters, Brown passed the entrance exams.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=40}} Brown enlisted in the [[United States Navy Reserve|U.S. Naval Reserve]] on 8 July 1946 {{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}} and was admitted to the aviation program, becoming a [[Seaman Apprentice]] in the U.S. Navy and a member of the school's [[Naval Reserve Officer Training Corps]] (NROTC) program. A $50 monthly stipend allowed him to quit his jobs and complete his architectural engineering degree in 1947.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=40}} At this time, the NROTC was the normal route to a regular Naval commission, but only 14 out of more than 5,600 NROTC students in 1947 were black.{{sfn|MacGregor|1981|pp=246â€“247}}

== Career ==
On 15 March 1947, Brown reported to [[Glenview Naval Air Station]] in [[Glenview, Cook County, Illinois|Glenview, Illinois]], for [[Naval Flight Officer]] training.{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}} There, his enlistment ended 15 April and Brown reverted to the rank of [[midshipman]], becoming the only African American in the program. Although he anticipated antagonism, he found the other cadets were generally friendly and welcoming.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=40}} He found many of the black cooks and janitors hostile to him, however, possibly due to jealousy.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=38}} Brown got his first flight time aboard a [[Stearman N2S]] [[trainer aircraft]].{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=42}}

[[File:Jesse L. Brown Commissioned.jpg|thumb|Brown is commissioned aboard the USS ''Leyte'' in 1949|left|alt=Three man stand on the deck of a ship, one with his arm raised and another reading from a paper.]]
In spite of the rigors of the initial training, Brown was encouraged by instructors and completed the first phase of training, transferring to [[Ottumwa Naval Air Station]] in [[Ottumwa, Iowa]], for the next phase.{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}} The Ottumwa training involved intense physical fitness and technical training, which Brown completed.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=40}} Thereafter, he was moved to [[Pensacola Naval Air Station]] in [[Pensacola, Florida]], to train in aircraft flight.

In Pensacola, Brown and Nix married in secret, as Naval Cadets were not allowed to marry until their training was complete, under threat of immediate dismissal. Nix took a room in Pensacola, and the two visited one another on weekends.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} In spite of overt racism from at least one instructor and several classmates at this posting,{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}} Brown completed the rigorous training in August 1947.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}}

By June 1948, Brown had begun training for [[carrier-based aircraft]], and hoped to fly either the [[F4U Corsair]] or [[F6F Hellcat]], both of which were fighters. He trained in carrier takeoffs and landings aboard the light carrier {{USS|Wright|CVL-49|6}},{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=161}} after which he was sent to [[Jacksonville, Florida]], for final flight qualifications. On 21 October 1948, he completed his training and was given his [[Naval Aviator Badge]].{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=60}}{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}}{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} This accomplishment was widely publicized, and Brown became known nationally. The [[Associated Press]] profiled him and his photograph appeared in [[Life Magazine|''Life'' magazine]]. Author [[Theodore Taylor (author)|Theodore Taylor]] later wrote that through Brown's efforts to become a pilot, he had broken the "[[color barrier]]" which had been longstanding and preventing blacks in naval aviation.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=xii}}

Brown was [[Commissioned officer|commissioned]] as an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]] in the U.S. Navy on 26 April 1949.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=60}} He was assigned to [[Naval Air Station Quonset Point|Quonset Point Naval Air Station]] in [[Quonset, Rhode Island]],{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} as a part of the [[U.S. Atlantic Fleet]]. Brown reported that incidents of racism and discrimination, which had been harsh late in his training, were substantially relieved once he became an officer.{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=395}} Following his commissioning, Brown was assigned to temporary duty at [[Norfolk Naval Air Station]] in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=181}} His daughter, Pamela Elise Brown, was born in December.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} In January 1949, Brown was assigned to [[VF-32|Fighter Squadron 32]] aboard the {{USS|Leyte|CV-32|6}}.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} Over the next 18 months, the unit conducted numerous training exercises along the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], many of them taking place at [[Quonset Point]]. Brown reported here his superiors treated him fairly and held others to equal standards. The unit trained rigorously in aircraft maneuvers.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=185}}

By the outbreak of the [[Korean War]], he had gained a reputation among the others in the squadron as an experienced pilot and a capable section leader.{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=396}} He was well-liked among other pilots and the black stewards and support staff of the carrier. Brown did not socialize much with the other pilots, however, and was known to spend as much time as possible visiting his wife. He was able to reveal his marriage following his commissioning.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=120}}{{sfn|Tillman|2002|p=209}}

=== Korean War ===

[[File:Jesse L. Brown in cockpit.jpg|thumb|Brown in the cockpit of his F4U Corsair in Korea in late 1950]]
[[File:ENS Jesse L. Brown USS Leyte (CV-32).jpg|thumb|Brown in the [[ready room]] of the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Leyte|CV-32}}.]]
{{see also|Initial phase of the Korean War}}

On the night of 25 June 1950, ten divisions of the [[North Korean People's Army]] launched a full-scale invasion of the nation's neighbor to the south, the [[Republic of Korea]]. The force of 89,000&nbsp;men moved in six columns, catching the [[Republic of Korea Army]] by surprise, resulting in a rout. The smaller South Korean army suffered from widespread lack of organization and equipment, and was unprepared for war.{{sfn|Alexander|2003|p=1}} The numerically superior North Korean forces destroyed isolated resistance from the 38,000&nbsp;South Korean soldiers on the front before it began moving steadily south.{{sfn|Alexander|2003|p=2}} Most of South Korea's forces retreated in the face of the invasion.{{sfn|Appleman|1998|p=36}} The North Koreans were well on their way to South Korea's capital of [[Seoul]] within hours, forcing the government and its shattered army to retreat farther south.{{sfn|Appleman|1998|p=36}}

To prevent South Korea's collapse the [[United Nations Security Council]] voted [[UNSCR 82|to send military forces]]. The [[United States Seventh Fleet]] dispatched [[Task Force 77 (U.S. Navy)|Task Force 77]], led by the [[fleet carrier]] {{USS|Valley Forge|CV-45|6}}; the British [[Far East Fleet]] dispatched several ships, including {{HMS|Triumph|R16|6}}, to provide air and naval support.{{sfn|Malkasian|2001|p=23}} Although the navies blockaded North Korea and launched aircraft to delay the North Korean forces, these efforts alone did not stop the North Korean Army juggernaut on its southern advance.{{sfn|Malkasian|2001|p=24}} U.S. President [[Harry S. Truman]] ordered ground troops into the country to supplement the air support.{{sfn|Varhola|2000|p=3}} All U.S. Navy units, including the ''Leyte'', were placed on alert.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} At the time, the ship was in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and Brown did not expect to be deployed to Korea, but on 8 August a relief carrier arrived in the area and the ''Leyte'' was ordered to Korea.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=117}} Commanders felt the pilots on the carrier were better trained, and hence needed in the theater. The ship sailed from the [[Strait of Gibraltar]] across the Atlantic Ocean and to Quonset, then through the [[Panama Canal]] and to San Diego, California, Hawaii, and Japan before arriving in Korea around 8 October.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=118}}

The ship joined Task Force 77 off the northeast coast of the [[Korean Peninsula]], part of a fleet of 17 ships from the Seventh Fleet, including the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Philippine Sea|CV-47|6}}, [[battleship]] {{USS|Missouri|BB-63|6}} and [[cruiser]] {{USS|Juneau|CL-119|6}}.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=1}} Brown flew 20 missions in-country.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} These missions included attacks on communication lines, troop concentrations, and military installations around [[Wonsan]], [[Chongpu]], [[Songjim]], and [[Senanju]].{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=396}}

Following the entrance of the People's Republic of China into the war in late November 1950, Brown and his squadron were dispatched to the [[Chosin Reservoir]], where an [[Battle of Chosin Reservoir|intense campaign]] was being fought between the [[People's Volunteer Army]] and the [[US X Corps]].{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} Approximately 100,000 Chinese troops had surrounded 15,000 U.S. troops, and Brown and other pilots on the ''Leyte'' flew dozens of [[close air support]] missions every day to prevent the Chinese from overrunning the U.S. troops.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=2}}{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=61}}

=== Death ===

[[File:Thomas J Hudner 1950.jpg|thumb|[[Thomas J. Hudner, Jr.]], Brown's wingman, who was awarded the [[Medal of Honor]] for attempting to save him|left]]
{{main|Battle of Chosin Reservoir}}

On 4 December 1950, Brown was part of a six-aircraft flight supporting [[U.S. Marine Corps]] ground troops trapped by Chinese forces.{{sfn|Dwight|Sewell|2009|p=397}} At 13:38 [[Korea Standard Time|KST]], Brown took off from the ''Leyte'' with squadron [[executive officer]] [[Lieutenant Commander]] [[Richard L. Cevoli|Dick Cevoli]], [[lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] George Hudson, Lieutenant Junior Grade Bill Koenig, Ensign Ralph McQueen, and [[Lieutenant Junior Grade]] [[Thomas J. Hudner, Jr.]], who was Brown's [[wingman]].{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=3}} During this flight, Brown had the call sign "Iroquois 13".{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=6}} The flight traveled {{convert|100|mi}} from the Task Force's location to the Chosin Reservoir, flying 35 to 40 minutes through very harsh wintery conditions to the vicinity of the villages of Yudam-ni and Hagaru-ri. The flight began searching for targets along the west side of the reservoir, decreasing their altitude to {{convert|700|ft}}.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=4}} The mission was a three-hour [[search and destroy]] flight as well as an attempt to probe Chinese troop strength in the area.{{sfn|Tillman|2002|p=209}}{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=121}}

Although the flight spotted no Chinese, at 14:40 Koenig radioed that Brown appeared to be trailing fuel.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=121}} The damage had likely come by [[small arms]] fire from Chinese infantry, who were known to hide in the snow and to ambush passing aircraft by firing in unison.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=120}} At least one bullet had ruptured a fuel line. Brown, losing fuel pressure and increasingly unable to control the aircraft, dropped his [[drop tank|external fuel tank]]s and rockets and attempted to land the craft in a snow-covered clearing on the side of a mountain. Brown crashed into a bowl-shaped valley at approximately {{coord|40|36|N|127|06|E}}.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=121}}{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=5}} The aircraft broke up violently upon impact and was destroyed.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=6}} In the crash, Brown's leg was pinned beneath the [[fuselage]] of the aircraft, and he stripped off his helmet and gloves in an attempt to free himself, before waving to the other pilots, who were circling close overhead.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} The other pilots had thought he had died in the crash.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=121}} Brown had [[crash landing|crash-landed]] near Somong-ni, {{convert|15|mi}} behind Chinese lines in {{convert|15|Â°F|Â°C}} weather,{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=122}} and the other pilots began a [[Mayday]] radio to any heavy transport aircraft in the area as they canvassed the mountain for any sign of Chinese ground forces who might threaten Brown.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=7}} They received a signal that a rescue helicopter would come as soon as possible, but Brown's aircraft was smoking and a fire had started near its internal fuel tanks.{{sfn|Tillman|2002|p=209}}{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=122}}

Before it became clear Brown was seriously injured, Hudner attempted in vain to rescue Brown by radioing him instructions for escaping his damaged aircraft. Hudner then intentionally crash-landed his aircraft, ran to Brown's side and attempted to wrestle him free from the wreck. While Brown's condition worsened by the minute, Hudner attempted in vain to put out the aircraft fire using snow and to pull Brown from the aircraft. In great pain, Brown began slipping in and out of consciousness.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=61}} A rescue helicopter arrived around 15:00; its pilot Lieutenant Charles Ward and Hudner were unable to put out the engine fire with a fire extinguisher, and tried unsuccessfully to free Brown with an axe for 45 minutes. They even considered, at Brown's request, amputating his trapped leg.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=123}} Brown lost consciousness shortly thereafter. His last known words to Hudner were, "Tell Daisy I love her."{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}}{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=61}} The helicopter, which was unable to operate in the darkness, was forced to return to base at nightfall with Hudner, leaving Brown behind. Brown is believed to have died shortly thereafter of his injuries and exposure to the extreme cold. No Chinese forces threatened the site, likely owing to the heavy air presence of Brown and Hudner's unit.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=124}}

Hudner begged superiors to allow him to return to the wreck to help extract Brown, but he was not allowed, as other officers feared an ambush of the vulnerable helicopters resulting in casualties. To prevent the body and the aircraft from falling into Chinese or North Korean hands, the U.S. Navy bombed the aircraft with [[napalm]] two days later, with pilots reportedly reciting the [[Lord's Prayer]] over the radio as they watched Brown's body be consumed by flames.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=62}} The pilots observed that Brown's body was still stuck in the aircraft, but his clothes were gone. The remains of both Brown and the aircraft were never recovered.{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=125}} Brown was the first African-American U.S. Navy officer killed in the war.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=62}}{{sfn|Ecker|2004|p=69}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Defense Casualty Analysis System (DCAS) Public Use File, 1950â€“2005|url=http://aad.archives.gov/aad/fielded-search.jsp?dt=2514&tf=F&cat=all&bc=sl|publisher=US National Archives|accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref>

== Legacy ==

{{quote box|width=30em|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|quote="He died in the wreckage of his airplane with courage and unfathomable dignity. He willingly gave his life to tear down barriers to freedom of others."|source=â€”Hudner, speaking of Brown 17 February 1973, at the commissioning of the USS ''Jesse L. Brown''}}

For his actions in Korea leading up to his death, Brown was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]], the [[Purple Heart Medal]], and the [[Air Medal]].{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=38}} For the failed rescue attempt, Hudner received the [[Medal of Honor]], the highest valor award presented by the [[U.S. military]].{{sfn|Smith|2004|p=115}}{{sfn|Tillman|2002|p=208}}{{sfn|Ecker|2004|p=70}}

Brown's shipmates memorialized him in a shipwide newspaper as "a Christian soldier, a gentleman, a shipmate, and friend&nbsp;... His courage and faith&nbsp;... shone like a beacon for all to see."{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} As word of his death spread, Brown inspired numerous other African Americans to become pilots, notably Seaman Apprentice [[Frank E. Petersen]]. Petersen would become the first African-American Marine Corps aviator and the first African-American Marine Corps general, being graduated from the Naval Aviation Training Program in 1952 and retiring from the military after 38 years in 1988 with the rank of [[Lieutenant General (United States)|lieutenant general]].{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}}

On 17 February 1973, the Navy commissioned the {{sclass|Knox|frigate}} {{USS|Jesse L. Brown|FF-1089}}, the third U.S. ship named in honor of an African American.<ref>[http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/prs-tpic/af-amer/afa-ship.htm USS Jesse L. Brown (DE-1089)]. ''Naval History and Heritage Command Photograph'', catalog #NH 96767.</ref> Present at the commissioning ceremony in [[Boston, Massachusetts]], were Daisy Brown Thorne (who had remarried), Pamela Brown, and Hudner, who gave a dedication.{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=41}} The ship was decommissioned on 27 July 1994 and renamed the ''Damiyat'' after being commissioned with the Egyptian navy.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=62}}{{sfn|Fannin|Gubert|Sawyer|2001|p=42}}

An extensive biography of Brown later was compiled by author [[Theodore Taylor (author)|Theodore Taylor]], who had served in Korea and had been deeply moved by the news of Brown's death at the time. Taylor interviewed many of Brown's closest friends and family and consulted Daisy Brown's personal diary and records from the ''Leyte'''s ship log while preparing his 300-page book, published in 2007.{{sfn|Taylor|2007|p=xiii}}

In July 2013, Hudner visited Pyongyang in an attempt to recover Brown's remains from the crash site. He was told by North Korean authorities to return in September when the weather is more predictable.<ref>[2013 News reports concerning Ensign Brown: http://www.newstimes.com/news/world/article/Vet-returns-to-NKorea-for-1st-black-Navy-aviator-4674235.php]</ref><ref>http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/30/world/asia/six-decades-after-korean-war-a-second-rescue-attempt.html</ref>

